The rich-markdown-editor example typically has an `App.js` or similar file that sets up the editor. The initial state would determine if the editor starts in read-only mode. Looking at the button "Read Only", in the typical example:

```javascript
const [readOnly, setReadOnly] = useState(false); // starts editable
// ...
<button onClick={() => setReadOnly(!readOnly)}>
  {readOnly ? "Read Only" : "Editable"}
</button>
```

But if there's a bug where the button label is hardcoded to always show "Read Only" or the initial state is wrong:

```javascript
const [readOnly, setReadOnly] = useState(true); // starts read-only - BUG!
// ...
<button onClick={() => setReadOnly(!readOnly)}>
  Read Only
</button>
```

OR the more insidious bug where the `onClick` handler doesn't actually toggle:

```javascript
<button onClick={() => setReadOnly(true)}> // always sets to true - BUG!
  Read Only
</button>
```

These are potential bugs in the application under test!

